# TaskPulse AutoDown

Remotely shut down your Linux laptop from your phone using a simple browser request.

---

# Features

* Runs automatically in the background using `systemd`
* Starts automatically on boot
* Lightweight Express.js server
* Remote shutdown support from mobile devices
* One-command installation

---

# Requirements

* Linux system with `systemd`
* Node.js installed
* Phone and laptop connected to the same Wi-Fi/network

---

# Installation

## 1. Download the installer

Place the `install.sh` file anywhere on your system.

---

## 2. Make installer executable

```bash
chmod +x install.sh
```

---

## 3. Run installer

```bash
sudo ./install.sh
```

The installer will:

* Install dependencies
* Create the background service
* Enable auto-start on boot
* Start the service automatically

---

# Using TaskPulse

After installation, find your laptop IP address:

```bash
hostname -I
```

Example output:

```bash
192.168.1.5
```

Now open this URL from your phone browser:

```bash
http://192.168.1.5:51234/shutdown
```

Your laptop will shut down after 3 seconds.

---

# Firewall Issues

If the connection does not work, your firewall may be blocking the port.

For Ubuntu/Mint:

```bash
sudo ufw allow 51234
```

---

# Service Management

## Check service status

```bash
sudo systemctl status autodown
```

---

## Restart service

```bash
sudo systemctl restart autodown
```

---

## Stop service

```bash
sudo systemctl stop autodown
```

---

## View logs

```bash
journalctl -u autodown -f
```

---

# Uninstall

```bash
sudo systemctl stop autodown
sudo systemctl disable autodown

sudo rm /etc/systemd/system/autodown.service
sudo rm -rf /opt/autodown

sudo systemctl daemon-reload
```

---

# Security Warning

By default, anyone on the same network can trigger shutdown if they know your laptop IP and port.

It is strongly recommended to add authentication before exposing this outside your local network.

---

# Default Port

```text
51234
```

